\f1\b\fs24 \cf0 1. The Dockerfile: Packaging the App\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 We'll create a\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 Dockerfile
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0to build an image for your app. The strategy is to use a multi-stage build. This is a best practice that keeps the final image incredibly small and secure.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa60\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Stage 1 (Builder):
\f0\b0 \'a0We'll use a Node.js image just to install the dependencies needed to\'a0
\f4\i build
\f0\i0 \'a0the React app (like TypeScript). We'll run a build command that transforms your\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 .tsx
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0files into optimized, static JavaScript, HTML, and CSS.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f3\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Stage 2 (Final Image):
\f0\b0 \'a0We'll use a super lightweight\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 nginx:alpine
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0image. Nginx is a high-performance web server perfect for serving static files. We will copy\'a0
\f4\i only the built files
\f0\i0 \'a0from Stage 1 into this final image. This means the final image doesn't contain Node.js or any development clutter.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This approach ensures the image is optimized for your M3's\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 arm64
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0architecture because we'll be using official multi-arch images.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs24 \cf0 2. The Docker Compose Service: Running the App\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

