\f1\b\fs24 \cf0 3. The Big Challenge: Handling the API Key\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 Your current code reads the API key from\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 process.env.API_KEY
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 . This is a Node.js concept. Once the app is built into static files and served by Nginx, there's no Node.js environment to provide that variable.\
The solution is to inject the key at\'a0
\f4\i runtime
\f0\i0 \'a0(when the container starts). Here\'92s how:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa60\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f3\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Create a Startup Script (
\f6 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 entrypoint.sh
\f3 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 ):
\f0\b0 \'a0This small script will run every time the container starts. Its job is to find a placeholder in one of the built JavaScript files and replace it with the actual API key that Docker Compose passes in.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f3\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Use a Placeholder in the Code:
\f0\b0 \'a0We'll modify\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 services/geminiService.ts
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0to use a unique placeholder like\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 __GEMINI_API_KEY__
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0instead of\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 process.env.API_KEY
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 .\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f3\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Secure the Key:
\f0\b0 \'a0In your project directory, you'll create a\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 .env
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 \'a0file (which you should\'a0
\f3\b never
\f0\b0 \'a0commit to Git) with one line:\'a0
\f2 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 GEMINI_API_KEY=your-actual-api-key-here
\f0 \cf0 \cb1 \strokec2 . Docker Compose will automatically read this file and make the variable available to the container.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa360\partightenfactor0
\cf0 This is a secure and standard way to handle secrets with Docker. The key lives on your machine, not in the image.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

